 the stunning paradox evident in the simultaneous erasure (in official circles) and ongoing fascination (in the popular imagination) with the nameless people who both define and fall outside of traditional norms of national identity. The book traces the legacy of these extraordinary figures in popular histories and legends, the Inquisition, ballads such as "La Adelita" and "La Cucaracha," iconic performers like Toña la Negra, and musical genres such as the son jarocho and danzón. This study is the first of its kind to draw attention to art's crucial role in bearing witness to the rich heritage of blacks and women in contemporary México.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArt and societyxHistoryxMexico. 0aArt and societyzMexicoxHistory. 0aBlack people in art. 0aBlacks in art. 0aRacially mixed womenxHistoryxMexico. 0aRacially mixed womenzMexicoxHistory. 0aSex rolexHistoryxMexico. 0aSex rolezMexicoxHistory. 0aWomen in art. 0aWomen revolutionariesxHistoryxMexico. 0aWomen revolutionarieszMexicoxHistory. 0aWomen soldiersxHistoryxMexico. 0aWomen soldierszMexicoxHistory. 0aWomenxHistoryxMexico. 0aWomenzMexicoxHistory. 0aWomen, BlackxHistoryxMexico. 0aWomen, BlackzMexicoxHistory. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438463599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438463599/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles